concept_explanation.first_class:
Let's define the simplest possible class:

```java
public class Dog {
    String name;
    int age;

    void bark() {
        System.out.println(name + " says: Woof!");
    }
}
```

Breakdown:
- `public class Dog` — declares a class named Dog
- `String name` and `int age` — **fields** (also called instance variables). Each Dog object will have its OWN name and age.
- `void bark()` — an **instance method**. Notice: no `static` keyword. Why? Because this method belongs to each individual Dog object, not the class itself.

Now let's USE this class:

```java
public class App {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Dog d1 = new Dog();   // Create a Dog object
        d1.name = "Rex";       // Set its name field
        d1.age = 3;

        Dog d2 = new Dog();
        d2.name = "Buddy";
        d2.age = 5;

        d1.bark();   // Rex says: Woof!
        d2.bark();   // Buddy says: Woof!
    }
}
```

What happened:
- `new Dog()` creates a NEW Dog object
- `d1` is a REFERENCE to that object (variable points to it)
- `d1.name = "Rex"` accesses the name field of d1 specifically — dot notation
- `d1.bark()` calls bark() on d1. Inside bark, `name` refers to d1's name ("Rex").
- `d2` is a SEPARATE object with its own name and age
- Each Dog has independent state

concept_explanation.instance_methods:
**Instance methods** operate on a specific object. They can access that object's fields directly by name.

```java
public class Circle {
    double radius;

    double area() {
        return Math.PI * radius * radius;
    }

    double circumference() {
        return 2 * Math.PI * radius;
    }
}
```

Note how `area()` uses `radius` directly — no need to pass it as a parameter. It's a FIELD of the same object the method belongs to.

Using:

```java
Circle c = new Circle();
c.radius = 5;
System.out.println(c.area());           // 78.54...
System.out.println(c.circumference());  // 31.42...
```

**Compare to procedural style** (last module):

```java
// Old way — procedural
public static double area(double radius) {
    return Math.PI * radius * radius;
}
// Caller: area(5)

// New way — object-oriented
Circle c = new Circle();
c.radius = 5;
c.area();
```

With one object, the procedural way is shorter. With many objects (50 circles, each with different radii), the OOP way is dramatically cleaner — radius is BOUND to its circle, not separate data you must keep track of.

**The key shift**: methods don't operate on data passed in — they operate on the object's OWN data.

concept_explanation.instance_vs_static_revisited:
Module 2 introduced static methods. Now you see the difference:

**Static method**: belongs to the CLASS. No object needed to call.

```java
public class MathUtils {
    public static int square(int n) {
        return n * n;
    }
}
// Call: MathUtils.square(5)
```

**Instance method**: belongs to an OBJECT. Need an object to call.

```java
public class Circle {
    double radius;

    double area() {  // no static keyword
        return Math.PI * radius * radius;
    }
}
// Call: c.area() — where c is a Circle object
```

**When to use each**:
- Static: utility functions that don't need object state (Math.sqrt, Math.max)
- Instance: methods that operate on a specific object's data (c.area)

**Why your main method is static**: Java needs to start somewhere — it can't create an object before any code has run. So `main` is static, called by the JVM without any object. From main, you THEN create objects.

**Static fields** (like `static int count` from Module 2): shared across all objects — really, they belong to the class. Used for counters, constants, shared resources. We'll see more of these soon.

concept_explanation.multiple_objects:
The power of classes: easily create many objects.

```java
Dog[] dogs = new Dog[3];
dogs[0] = new Dog();
dogs[0].name = "Rex";
dogs[0].age = 3;

dogs[1] = new Dog();
dogs[1].name = "Buddy";
dogs[1].age = 5;

dogs[2] = new Dog();
dogs[2].name = "Luna";
dogs[2].age = 2;

for (Dog d : dogs) {
    d.bark();
}
```

Output:
```
Rex says: Woof!
Buddy says: Woof!
Luna says: Woof!
```

This is HUGE. With parallel arrays, you'd have:
```java
String[] names = {"Rex", "Buddy", "Luna"};
int[] ages = {3, 5, 2};
// To bark: System.out.println(names[i] + " says: Woof!");
```

The data is split across arrays. With objects: each Dog is self-contained.

**Important**: `Dog[] dogs = new Dog[3]` creates an array of 3 dog REFERENCES, all initially null. You must `new Dog()` for each slot. Otherwise: NullPointerException when you try to use `dogs[i].something`.

step_by_step_solution.details:
Create the class structure. For now, this goes in the SAME file as your main class (Java allows multiple classes per file, though only one can be `public`).

```java
class Product {
    int id;
    String name;
    int stock;
    double price;

    String describe() {
        return "#" + id + " " + name + " — Stock: " + stock + ", Price: ₹" + price;
    }
}
```

The class has:
- Four fields representing what a Product 'has'
- One method representing what a Product 'can do' (describe itself)

Note: `class Product` (no `public`) because it's a helper class in the same file. The `public class` is your main class.

Main now uses Product objects instead of parallel arrays:

```java
public class InventoryOOP {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Product[] catalog = new Product[5];
        // ... populate, then use
    }
}
```

`Product[] catalog` is an array of Product REFERENCES. We need to create actual Product objects to fill it.

```java
catalog[0] = new Product();
catalog[0].id = 101;
catalog[0].name = "Wireless Mouse";
catalog[0].stock = 45;
catalog[0].price = 599.99;

catalog[1] = new Product();
catalog[1].id = 102;
catalog[1].name = "USB-C Cable";
catalog[1].stock = 12;
catalog[1].price = 249.0;

catalog[2] = new Product();
catalog[2].id = 103;
catalog[2].name = "Notebook";
catalog[2].stock = 87;
catalog[2].price = 89.5;

catalog[3] = new Product();
catalog[3].id = 104;
catalog[3].name = "Mechanical Keyboard";
catalog[3].stock = 8;
catalog[3].price = 4500.0;

catalog[4] = new Product();
catalog[4].id = 105;
catalog[4].name = "Desk Lamp";
catalog[4].stock = 23;
catalog[4].price = 1299.0;
```

Verbose — and we'll fix this with **constructors** next topic. For now, manual field assignment works.

Notice we MUST `new Product()` for each slot. Skipping that line would leave the slot null, and accessing `catalog[0].id` would throw NullPointerException.

```java
System.out.println("=== INVENTORY ===");
for (Product p : catalog) {
    System.out.println(p.describe());
}
```

Clean. The for-each gives us each Product. We call `describe()` on it — the method uses the object's own fields internally.

**Old (parallel arrays, from Module 3.2)**:
```java
int[] productIds = {101, 102, 103, 104, 105};
String[] names = {"Wireless Mouse", "USB-C Cable", ...};
int[] stocks = {45, 12, 87, 8, 23};
double[] prices = {599.99, 249.0, 89.5, 4500.0, 1299.0};

for (int i = 0; i < productIds.length; i++) {
    System.out.println("#" + productIds[i] + " " + names[i] 
        + " — Stock: " + stocks[i] + ", Price: ₹" + prices[i]);
}
```

**New (object array)**:
```java
for (Product p : catalog) {
    System.out.println(p.describe());
}
```

Differences:
- Old: 4 arrays must be kept in sync. New: 1 array of self-contained objects.
- Old: print logic inline, with index gymnastics. New: each Product describes itself.
- Old: adding 'category' means a 5th array everywhere. New: add a field to Product.
- Old: sorting requires sorting all 4 arrays together. New: sort the array of products.

This is the OOP advantage.

worked_example.final_code:
class Product {
    int id;
    String name;
    int stock;
    double price;

    String describe() {
        return "#" + id + " " + name + " — Stock: " + stock + ", Price: ₹" + price;
    }
}

public class InventoryOOP {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Product[] catalog = new Product[5];

        catalog[0] = new Product();
        catalog[0].id = 101;
        catalog[0].name = "Wireless Mouse";
        catalog[0].stock = 45;
        catalog[0].price = 599.99;

        catalog[1] = new Product();
        catalog[1].id = 102;
        catalog[1].name = "USB-C Cable";
        catalog[1].stock = 12;
        catalog[1].price = 249.0;

        catalog[2] = new Product();
        catalog[2].id = 103;
        catalog[2].name = "Notebook";
        catalog[2].stock = 87;
        catalog[2].price = 89.5;

        catalog[3] = new Product();
        catalog[3].id = 104;
        catalog[3].name = "Mechanical Keyboard";
        catalog[3].stock = 8;
        catalog[3].price = 4500.0;

        catalog[4] = new Product();
        catalog[4].id = 105;
        catalog[4].name = "Desk Lamp";
        catalog[4].stock = 23;
        catalog[4].price = 1299.0;

        System.out.println("=== INVENTORY ===");
        for (Product p : catalog) {
            System.out.println(p.describe());
        }
    }
}

